The new species is similar to those species bearing a simple male epiproct. It differs from the previous species by the apex of the male epiproct only plump without being vertically expanded (

), and bears a circular imprint at the bottom of the epiproctal concavity (

); from 

R. setiformis
Qin, Jiang, Liu & Li, 2018

by the apex of the male epiproct swell not depressed (

, 

), the concavity of the male epiproct being not narrow and prolonged from base to apex; and from 

R. duxiu

in the shape of the male epiproctal concavity and the length of the female subgenital plate.

